This notebook is a template with each step that you need to complete for the project.

Please fill in your code where there are explicit ? markers in the notebook. You are welcome to add more cells and code as you see fit.

Once you have completed all the code implementations, please export your notebook as a HTML file so the reviews can view your code. Make sure you have all outputs correctly outputted.

File-> Export Notebook As... -> Export Notebook as HTML

Completing the code template and writeup template will cover all of the rubric points for this project.

The rubric contains "Stand Out Suggestions" for enhancing the project beyond the minimum requirements. The stand out suggestions are optional. If you decide to pursue the "stand out suggestions", you can include the code in this notebook and also discuss the results in the writeup file.

Data Fields¶

datetime - hourly date + timestamp

season - 1 = spring, 2 = summer, 3 = fall, 4 = winter

holiday - whether the day is considered a holiday

workingday - whether the day is neither a weekend nor holiday

weather -

1: Clear, Few clouds, Partly cloudy, Partly cloudy
2: Mist + Cloudy, Mist + Broken clouds, Mist + Few clouds, Mist
3: Light Snow, Light Rain + Thunderstorm + Scattered clouds, Light Rain + Scattered clouds
4: Heavy Rain + Ice Pallets + Thunderstorm + Mist, Snow + Fog

temp - temperature in Celsius

atemp - "feels like" temperature in Celsius

humidity - relative humidity

windspeed - wind speed

casual - number of non-registered user rentals initiated (ignored)

registered - number of registered user rentals initiated (ignored)

count - number of total rentals

Step 3: Train a model using AutoGluon’s Tabular Prediction¶

Requirements:

  • We are prediting count, so it is the label we are setting.
  • Ignore casual and registered columns as they are also not present in the test dataset.
  • Use the root_mean_squared_error as the metric to use for evaluation.
  • Set a time limit of 10 minutes (600 seconds).
  • Use the preset best_quality to focus on creating the best model.
In [12]:
label = 'count'
train_data = train.drop(columns=['casual', 'registered'])
In [13]:
predictor = TabularPredictor(label=label, eval_metric='root_mean_squared_error').fit(
    train_data=train_data,
    time_limit=600,
    presets='best_quality'
)

Step 4: Exploratory Data Analysis and Creating an additional feature¶

  • Any additional feature will do, but a great suggestion would be to separate out the datetime into hour, day, or month parts.
In [23]:
# Create a histogram of all features to show the distribution of each one relative to the data. This is part of the exploritory data analysis
train.hist(figsize=(20, 20))
Out[23]:
array([[<Axes: title={'center': 'datetime'}>,
        <Axes: title={'center': 'season'}>,
        <Axes: title={'center': 'holiday'}>],
       [<Axes: title={'center': 'workingday'}>,
        <Axes: title={'center': 'weather'}>,
        <Axes: title={'center': 'temp'}>],
       [<Axes: title={'center': 'atemp'}>,
        <Axes: title={'center': 'humidity'}>,
        <Axes: title={'center': 'windspeed'}>],
       [<Axes: title={'center': 'casual'}>,
        <Axes: title={'center': 'registered'}>,
        <Axes: title={'center': 'count'}>]], dtype=object)
  1. datetime Data is collected fairly consistently over time from 2011 to 2013.
  2. season Quite uniform distribution across the four seasons.
  3. holiday Holidays are infrequent.
  4. workingday Most observations are working day, similar to previous feature.
  5. weather The most frequent weather condition is presumably clear, few clouds. Mist, cloudy is also common. Light snow, rain less frequent. Heavy rain, ice pallets is extemely rare.
  6. temp Roughly normal distribution. Most between 10°C to 30°C.
  7. atemp Similar to temp. The peak is also 10-30°C range.
  8. humidity Left-skewed distribution with peak around 40-90% humidity. The presense of 0% humidity data might suggest missing data or errors.
  9. windspeed Right-skewed distribution with a large number of obervations having low wind speeds (0-20 km/h)
  10. count Highly right-skewed. Very high rental counts are much rarer than lower counts.

The count of bike rentals shows a strong positive correlation with both registered (0.97) and casual (0.69) users, and a moderate positive correlation with temp and atemp (0.39). Notably, temp and atemp are almost perfectly correlated. Furthermore, weather and humidity (0.41), and datetime and season (0.48) also exhibit expected moderate positive correlations. Other features generally show weaker linear relationships.

Observations based on barplots:

  1. hour/count These patterns reflect daily human activity:
  • High (7-9 AM & 4-7 PM): Peak commute hours for work/school.
  • Moderate (10 AM - 3 PM): Mid-day rentals for leisure, errands, or lunch breaks.
  • Low (0-6 AM & 8 PM - 12 AM): Overnight and late evening when most people are asleep or not commuting.
  1. dayofweek/count Bike rentals don't show a strong pattern by day of the week. However, demand is a bit higher on Thursdays, Fridays, and Saturdays, and lower on Sundays.
  2. month/count The month plot shows seasonal variations in data collection frequency. It clearly indicates more data points were recorded during warmer months (spring, summer, early autumn) and fewer during colder, winter months.
  3. year/count Year 2012 has higher bike demand as compared to 2011
  4. weather/count The bar plot for average bike rentals by weather shows clear days (1) have the highest count, and light adverse conditions (3) have the lowest. However, surprisingly, heavy adverse conditions (4) show a higher average count than light adverse, likely due to data sparsity in the extreme weather category

New Feature Engineering¶

In [38]:
def get_rush_hour(hour):
    if (6 <= hour <= 8) or (15 <= hour <=18): # High (7-9 AM & 4-7 PM)
        return 'high'
    elif 10 <= hour <= 14: # Moderate (10 AM - 3 PM)
        return 'mid'
    else: # Low (0-6 AM & 8 PM - 12 AM)
        return 'low'

train['activity_level'] = train['hour'].apply(get_rush_hour)
test['activity_level'] = test['hour'].apply(get_rush_hour)
